In[42]:
sns.countplot(data=penguins_clean, x="species")
plt.title("Count of Penguins by Species")
plt.show()

The bar plot shows how many penguins we have from each species.
The classes are not perfectly balanced, but each species (Adelie, Chinstrap, Gentoo) has a reasonable number of samples. This is helpful for building classification models because we are not trying to learn from only a few examples.

In[43]:

for col in numeric_cols:
    sns.histplot(
        data=penguins_clean,
        x=col,
        hue="species",
        kde=True,
        element="step"
    )
    plt.title(f"Distribution of {col} by Species")
    plt.show()
In[44]:
sns.pairplot(
    penguins_clean,
    vars=["bill_length_mm", "bill_depth_mm", "flipper_length_mm", "body_mass_g"],
    hue="species",
    corner=True
)
plt.suptitle("Relationships of Measurements by Species", y=1.02)
plt.show()

The histograms and pairplot show clear differences between species:

Gentoo penguins tend to have longer flippers and higher body mass.
Adelie and Chinstrap penguins have more overlap, but still show differences in bill length and bill depth.

These patterns suggest that physical measurements should be useful features for predicting species.

In[45]:
target_col = "species"
feature_cols = [
    "bill_length_mm",
    "bill_depth_mm",
    "flipper_length_mm",
    "body_mass_g",
    "island",
    "sex"
]

data = penguins_clean[feature_cols + [target_col]].copy()
data_encoded = pd.get_dummies(data, columns=["island", "sex"], drop_first=True)

X = data_encoded.drop(columns=[target_col])
y = data_encoded[target_col]

X.head(), y.head()

In[46]:
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X, y,
    test_size=0.25,
    random_state=42,
    stratify=y
)
numeric_features = ["bill_length_mm", "bill_depth_mm", "flipper_length_mm", "body_mass_g"]

scaler = StandardScaler()

X_train_scaled = X_train.copy()
X_test_scaled = X_test.copy()

X_train_scaled[numeric_features] = scaler.fit_transform(X_train[numeric_features])
X_test_scaled[numeric_features] = scaler.transform(X_test[numeric_features])

X_train_scaled.head()

In[47]:
log_reg = LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000, multi_class="multinomial")

log_reg.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
y_pred_log = log_reg.predict(X_test_scaled)

log_acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_log)
print(f"Logistic Regression Accuracy: {log_acc:.3f}")
print("\nClassification Report (Logistic Regression):")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_log))

In[48]:
cm_log = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_log, labels=log_reg.classes_)

In[49]:
tree_clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(
    max_depth=4,
    random_state=42
)

tree_clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred_tree = tree_clf.predict(X_test)

tree_acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_tree)
print(f"Decision Tree Accuracy: {tree_acc:.3f}")
print("\nClassification Report (Decision Tree):")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_tree))

In[51]:
results = pd.DataFrame({
    "Model": ["Logistic Regression", "Decision Tree"],
    "Accuracy": [log_acc, tree_acc]
})

results

In[52]:
sns.barplot(data=results, x="Model", y="Accuracy")
plt.ylim(0, 1)
plt.title("Model Accuracy Comparison")
plt.show()

Both models did a good job of predicting penguin species from the chosen features.

Logistic Regression achieved an accuracy of about 1

Decision Tree achieved an accuracy of about 0.976

The confusion matrices show where the models make mistakes.
Most predictions are correct, but some errors occur between Adelie and Chinstrap penguins, which sometimes have similar measurements.

Overall, logistic regression slightly outperforms the decision tree in this setup, but both models display that physical measurements and simple categorical features are strong predictors of species.
